of life is the act of an unwitting agent, and it necessarily meets with the violent incomprehension of the society it transforms. The tragedy of Antigone, the French Revolution and its aftermath (the Terror and the Napoleonic Wars), and wars generally are all examples of the tragically violent foundation of a new form of life. Moreover, Hegel does not claim that the foundation of modern ethical life is a fact of the past—it lies in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362603440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503626034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503626034/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles